The fourth generation BMW M3 was announced on the 2007 Geneva Auto Show (Switzerland, March 6-18th, 2007) with the BMW ''M3 concept''. As was the case with the E46 M3 Concept and E60 M5 Concept, the M3 Concept hid almost nothing of the looks of the production version, that had its world premiere on the 2007 Frankfurt Auto Show ''IAA'' (Germany, September 13 to 23rd).

Just as the previous M3 generations all introduced a completely new engine, the fourth generation M3 did the same: the [[BMW S65]] engine was introduced. This S65B40 is a naturally aspirated, high revving 4-litre V8 (based on the S85B50 5-litre V10 that powers the E60/E61 M5 and the E63/E64 M6 to date) delivers {{convert|414|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 8,300 rpm and peak torque is {{convert|400|Nm|lbft|abbr=on}} at 3,900 rpm, which represents a power increase of 22% over the E46 M3. The engine weighs {{convert|15|kg|lb|abbr=on}} less than the outgoing six cylinder for a total weight of {{convert|202|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. A six-speed manual transmission is standard. As from April 2008, BMW offers a new [[Getrag]] double-clutch gearbox, called M-DKG (Doppel-Kupplungs-Getriebe) or [[dual clutch transmission#BMW|M-DCT]] (Double Clutch Transmission) as an option, which reduces shift pauses to less than a tenth of a second and shortens the car's 0-{{convert|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} sprint time by 0.2 seconds vs. manual. It features both automatic and manual modes in a manner similar to the [[Electrohydraulic_manual_transmission#Use_in_road_cars|SMG]] gearboxes in the E36 and E46. The E92 M3 coupe inherits the carbon-fiber roof from the E46 CSL as part of the weight-saving program.  For 2009, the E9x M3 received the same revisions as the non-M 3 series.  The changes include revised front and rear bumpers, and LED tail lights.

[[Image:M3 Cabrio.JPG|thumb|left|The M3 Cabrio.]]
The new M3 is once again available as a 4-door sedan, based on the E90 3-Series, but unlike the regular models, this car shares the coupe's front end, including headlights. However, it does not get the 2-door's carbon-fiber roof. The E93 hardtop convertible version joins the lineup shortly after the E92's launch, while an E91 wagon is due in the first quarter of 2009. A CSL lightweight version is heavily debated and longed for amongst car enthusiasts, but while cars suspected to be the new M3 CSL have apparently been spotted at the famous Nordschleife (North Loop) of the [[N<U+00FC>rburgring|German N<U+00FC>rburgring]], the M division have stated that they do not plan to offer an e9x M3 CSL and are instead focussed on producing M versions of the X5 and X6 in a significant departure from M's historic practices<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.carmagazine.co.uk/Secret-new-cars/Search-Results/Spyshots/BMW-cancels-E92-M3-CSL/ | title = BMW <U+2018>cancels E92 M3 CSL' | publisher = Car Magazine | date = 26 August 2008}}.</ref>

[[BMW M]]otorsport announced in February 2008 that [[Rahal Letterman Racing]] will campaign two factory-backed E92 M3s in the [[American Le Mans Series]] in 2009, following a two-year absence by the brand.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.autoweek.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080206/FREE/913021814/1608/FREE | title = BMW returning to American Le Mans Series | publisher = AutoWeek | date = 6 February 2008 | accessdate = 2008-02-06}}</ref>

===E92 M3 GT2 ===

'''ALMS'''
[[Image:Rahal_Letterman_M3_GT2_at_Road_Atlanta_2009.jpg|thumb|left|Rahal Letterman M3 GT2 racing at the 2009 [[Petit Le Mans]].]]
The M3 GT2 is a version of the E93 M3 developed for the GT2 category of the American Le Mans Series. [[BMW M]]otorsport announced in February 2008 that [[Rahal Letterman Racing]] will campaign two M3 GT2s in the ALMS in 2009, following a two-year absence by the brand. <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.autoweek.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080206/FREE/913021814/1608/FREE | title = BMW returning to American Le Mans Series | publisher = AutoWeek | date = 6 February 2008 | accessdate = 2008-02-06}}</ref>

As in 2009, the BMW Rahal Letterman Racing Team, under the flag of BMW of North America, will send two BMW M3 GT2 cars into battle for the GT2 title in the ALMS 2010. In 2009 Bobby Rahal<U+2019>s team celebrated a one-two result at Road America and finished on the podium seven times. Next year the driving quartet will once again consist of Dirk M<U+00FC>ller, Tommy Milner, Bill Auberlen and Joey Hand.
<ref>{{cite web | url = hhttp://bmw-motorsport.com/ms/en/news/current/2009_12/2009_12_05.html?lity=tn_ms_sp_2_1_M | title = BMW Motorsport presents 2010 programme | publisher = BMW Motorsport | date = 05.12.2009  | accessdate = 05.12.2009 }}</ref>






'''Europe'''

[[Image:M3Gt2_Estoril.jpg|thumb|right|BMW M3 GT2 Testing in Estoril track Portugal]]

BMW will be represented at numerous GT events by its long-term test and development team Schnitzer Motorsport. The focus of this commitment is on the classic 24-hour races. As well as the 24-hour race at the N<U+00FC>rburgring, it is also planned for the BMW M3 GT2 to start in Le Mans and Spa-Francorchamps. BMW Motorsport is currently in positive discussions with organisers and governing bodies regarding the approval of the car.

In addition, and as preparation for these classics, the programme also includes race starts in the VLN Endurance Championship at the N<U+00FC>rburgring and in the Le Mans Series (LMS). J<U+00F6>rg M<U+00FC>ller and Dirk Werner, who joins the 2010 BMW works drivers line-up, will be the regular drivers for the GT races. Works drivers Andy Priaulx, Augusto Farfus and Dirk M<U+00FC>ller will also be involved with the GT programme. Uwe Alzen and Dirk Adorf complete the strong squad for the 24-hour race at the N<U+00FC>rburgring.<ref>{{cite web | url = hhttp://bmw-motorsport.com/ms/en/news/current/2009_12/2009_12_05.html?lity=tn_ms_sp_2_1_M | title = BMW Motorsport presents 2010 programme | publisher = BMW Motorsport | date = 05.12.2009  | accessdate = 05.12.2009 }}</ref>

===E92 M3 GT4 ===

[[BMW M]]otorsport announced on July 7, 2009 the launch of a line of BMW M3 race cars which meet the [[GT4 European Cup|FIA's GT4]] spec and are oriented for sale to private teams and drivers. The BMW M3 GT4 price is expected to be approximately 120,000 Euros.

"The new BMW M3 GT4 now also provides private teams with numerous opportunities," says BMW Motorsport Director [[Mario Theissen]]. "For over 50 years customer racing has been a cornerstone of BMW<U+2019>s motorsport programs. After all, what better global ambassador for the performance pedigree of BMW cars than a privateer who is competing for victory in a BMW vehicle."

On April 10 2009, the week after the debut of the GT4, BMW's Customer Racing program announed it had partnered with [[Schubert Motorsport]] (sponsored by [[Motorsport Arena Oschersleben]]) to run the BMW M3 GT4 in the annual [[24 Hours N<U+00FC>rburgring]] race SP10 class. The race took place on the weekend of May 23 and 24 in 2009, with drivers Jochen Ubler, Jorg Muller and Andy Priaulx at the wheel. The team finished sixth in their class and 153rd overall<ref>http://adac.24h-rennen.de/uploads/media/24h-Rennen-Gesamt-01Stunden.pdf</ref>.

The BMW M3 GT4 also raced in the [[ADAC Procar Series|ADAC]] Westfalenfahrt in April 2009 at [[N<U+00FC>rburgring|The Ring]], taking the win in the SP10 class and finishing 30th overall.

The M3 GT4 is offered in Europe as a [[Homologation (motorsport)|homologated]] production race car for sale to the general public. According to Larry Koch, BMW NA M-brand manager, a feasibility study is currently being conducted to evaluate the possible sale of the M3 GT4 in North America. However, without an FIA sanctioned GT4-class racing series in the USA, the sale of the M3 GT4 in the States is not likely.

===E90/E92 M3 performance===
*0-{{convert|60|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}: 4.4-4.2 seconds for the 2009 E90/E92 M3,<ref name="caranddriver.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/comparison_test/coupes/2009_porsche_911_carrera_vs_2009_bmw_m3_comparison_test+page-2.html |title=2009 Porsche 911 Carrera vs. 2009 BMW M3 - Coupes/Comparison Test/Reviews/Car and Driver |publisher=Car And Driver |date=2008-03-23 |accessdate=2009-06-12}}</ref>  5.1 sec for the convertible
*1/4&nbsp;mile: 12.7 seconds @ {{convert|183|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on|1}} <ref name="caranddriver.com"/>, Convertible: 13.1 @ {{convert|109|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on|1}}
*Top Speed: Electronically limited to {{convert|249|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}, delimited ~{{convert|290|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}+
*Skid Pad: 0.98 g
*Slalom: {{convert|114.9|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}

===E92 M3 GTS===
BMW announced the M3 GTS in November 2009. The car is powered by a 4.4-litre V8 based on the 4.0-litre engine found in the standard M3, which produces a maximum of 450 bhp. A total of only 99 units will be produced.
In Germany deliveries begin in May 2010 while other countries are scheduled for the summer. The BMW E92 M3 GTS will start at <U+20AC>115,000 per unit.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.inautonews.com/bmw-m3-gts-is-the-most-extreme-m3-ever | title = 
BMW M3 GTS is the most extreme M3 ever}}</ref> All E92 M3 GTS models have now been sold <ref>http://www.gtspirit.com/2010/01/26/sold-out-2011-bmw-m3-gts/</ref>.

==Critical reception==
The M3 has received nearly unanimous critical acclaim from motoring journalists for its performance, refinement, and practicality.  It is the only car on [[Seven Car Garage]] to receive 100% positive reviews.<ref>[http://sevencargarage.com/Vehicles/Small-Cars/bmw-m3-2009 Seven Car Garage - BMW M3]</ref>  Ezra Dyer of Automobile Magazine once suggested that "...car magazines generally regard the M3 the same way a four-year-old regards Santa Claus."<ref>[http://www.automobilemag.com/features/great_drives/0610_ezra_buys_an_m3/index.html What Do I Drive? Ezra Dyer Buys a Used BMW M3]</ref>

== BMW M3 Challenge ==
[[Image:BMW M3 Challenge.jpg|150px|thumb|left|BMW M3 Challenge PC Game]]
The "BMW M3 challenge" is a freeware racing game developed by BMW for simulation and entertainment purposes. The [[Personal computer|PC]] game includes single and multi-player modes.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bmw.com/com/en/newvehicles/mseries/m3coupe/2007/experience/game/content.html | title = BMW M3 Challenge the game}}</ref>

Developed by Blimey! Games and 10tacle Studios in cooperation with BMW engineers, it is a car simulation that reproduces real life car physics such as [[body roll]] and [[under/over-steer]].

It allows the player to perform advanced driving maneuvers such as feathering the brakes, moderating the clutch engagement level, or engine braking.

BMW M3 Challenge features a drivable representation of the GP portion of the famous [[N<U+00FC>rburgring]] German race track.

